post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_44553920_44554007_0": {"length": 27, "quality": 0.9642857142857143, "section_id": 456}, "so_44553920_44553920_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.8333333333333334, "section_id": 361}}, "n3337": {"so_44553920_44554007_0": {"length": 27, "quality": 0.9642857142857143, "section_id": 447}, "so_44553920_44553920_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.8333333333333334, "section_id": 351}}, "n4659": {"so_44553920_44554007_0": {"length": 28, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 479}, "so_44553920_44553920_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.8333333333333334, "section_id": 373}}}, "44553920": {"ViewCount": "56", "Body": "<p>It's written on cppreference that for post C++11 versions of the standard one of the cases when copy constructor is implicitly defined as deleted is the following (constructor for class T):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_44553920_44553920_0\">T has a user-defined move constructor or move assignment operator;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It seems to be true according to compilers, however I didn't manage to find it in the standard...</p>\n<p>The place seems to be 12.8/11 (at least for 14882:2011), all other cases seem to be there except the aforementioned one..</p>\n<p>Where should I look for this particular case?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "44554007", "Title": "Implicit copy constructor in presence of user-defined move constructor/assignment", "CreationDate": "2017-06-14T20:12:36.933", "Id": "44553920", "CommentCount": "0", "PostTypeId": "1", "ClosedDate": "2017-06-14T20:18:36.283", "LastActivityDate": "2017-06-14T20:17:58.513", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "4751585", "Tags": "<c++><c++11><c++14><language-lawyer><copy-constructor>", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "44554007": {"Id": "44554007", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>At least as of the draft I have handiest at the moment (N4618), it's at \u00a7[class.copy.ctor]/6:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_44553920_44554007_0\">If the class definition does not explicitly declare a copy constructor, a non-explicit one is declared implicitly. If the class definition declares a move constructor or move assignment operator, the implicitly declared copy constructor is defined as deleted; otherwise, it is defined as defaulted (8.4).</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2017-06-14T20:17:58.513", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2017-06-14T20:17:58.513", "ParentId": "44553920", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "179910"}});